# 🔥 Tech Lead Engineering Standards v2 (Pragmatic & Executable)

---

## 0. Non-Negotiables (Fail = Block PR)

- ❌ No tests → no merge
- ❌ No input validation → no merge
- ❌ Hidden side effects → no merge
- ❌ Breaking API/contracts → no merge
- ❌ Sensitive data in logs → no merge
- ❌ Unreadable code → no merge

---

# 1. System Design

## 1.1 Architecture Choice

- Default: **Modular Monolith**
- Microservices only if:
  - Independent teams
  - Real scaling needs
  - Clear bounded contexts

---

## 1.2 Base Structure

- Mandatory separation:
  - Domain
  - Application
  - Infrastructure

- Never mix business logic with infra

---

## 1.3 Core Design Rules

- Enforce SRP
- Prefer composition over inheritance
- Apply Dependency Inversion (DIP)
- Avoid cross-domain coupling
- Define explicit contracts between layers

---

## 1.4 Domain-Driven Design (DDD)

Use when:
- Complex business rules

Rules:
- Aggregates with clear invariants
- Avoid anemic models
- Explicit use cases (Application layer)

---

## 1.5 Integrations

- Use Anti-Corruption Layer
- Version all contracts

---

# 2. Code Quality

## 2.1 Structure

- Functions:
  - Single responsibility
  - < 30 lines
  - ≤ 3 nesting levels

- Classes:
  - Small
  - Cohesive
  - No God objects

---

## 2.2 Readability

- Must be understandable in one pass

Naming:
- Booleans → `isActive`, `hasAccess`
- Functions → `createUser`, `processPayment`

---

## 2.3 Critical Rules

- ❌ Boolean flags
- ❌ Magic numbers
- ❌ Hidden mutations

- ✅ Prefer:
  - Early returns
  - Pure functions
  - Immutability

---

## 2.4 DRY vs Clarity

- Clarity > DRY
- Abstract only when:
  - Real reuse
  - Reduced complexity

---

# 3. Data & Domain Modeling

- Use Value Objects
- Make invalid states impossible
- Validate at boundaries
- Prefer immutability

---

# 4. Testing Strategy

## Pyramid

- Unit → majority
- Integration → services
- E2E → critical paths only

---

## Rules

- Deterministic tests
- No time/random dependency
- Use DI for testability
- Cover edge cases

---

## Advanced

- Contract testing for APIs
- CI must block on failures

---

# 5. Security

- Always enforce Auth + Authorization
- Mandatory input validation
- Never expose:
  - Tokens
  - Secrets
  - Sensitive data

---

## Protection

- SQL/NoSQL Injection
- XSS
- CSRF / SSRF

---

## Infra

- TLS required
- Secret manager
- Least privilege (IAM)

---

# 6. Error Handling

- No generic errors
- Use typed domain errors
- Do not leak internals
- Fail fast when needed

---

# 7. Observability

- Structured logs
- Mandatory traceId
- Metrics:
  - Latency
  - Errors
  - Throughput

---

## Production

- Health checks
- Dashboards
- SLO-based alerts

---

# 8. Performance & Scaling

- Avoid N+1 queries
- Use pagination
- Proper indexing

---

## Scaling

- Prefer stateless services
- Use caching when needed
- Async via queues (Kafka/RabbitMQ)

---

## Rule

> Do not optimize before measuring

---

# 9. Resilience

- Mandatory timeouts
- Retry with exponential backoff
- Circuit breaker

---

## Rules

- Idempotency
- Handle concurrency
- Graceful degradation

---

# 10. CI/CD & DevOps

- Pipeline must include:
  - Tests
  - Lint
  - Security checks

---

## Deployment

- Feature flags
- Canary / Blue-Green
- Automatic rollback

---

# 11. API Design

- Predictable APIs
- Mandatory versioning
- Idempotency
- Pagination & filtering

---

## Contracts

- OpenAPI
- Schema validation

---

# 12. Data Management

- Versioned migrations
- Backward compatibility

---

## Rules

- Clear data ownership
- Defined retention policy
- LGPD compliance

---

# 13. Reliability & SRE

- Error budgets
- Track MTTR / MTBF
- Automate recovery

---

# 14. Cost Awareness

- Monitor cost per feature
- Avoid overengineering
- Use autoscaling wisely

---

# 15. Team Process

- Definition of Done required
- Structured code reviews
- Conventional commits

---

## Culture

- Blameless environment
- Clear ownership
- Continuous knowledge sharing

---

# 16. Product Alignment

- Engineering serves product
- Validate assumptions early
- Measure impact (KPIs)

---

# 17. Advanced Practices (Use When Justified)

- Load testing
- Chaos engineering
- Dark launches
- Feature toggles

---

# 18. Distributed Systems

- Understand CAP trade-offs
- Accept eventual consistency when needed

---

## Patterns

- Saga
- Outbox

---

## Guarantees

- Idempotency
- Safe reprocessing

---

# 19. Developer Experience (DX)

- Fast local setup
- Fast tests
- High feedback loop

---

# 20. Guiding Principles

- Simplicity > sophistication
- Clarity > abstraction
- Design for failure
- Optimize for change
- Make trade-offs explicit
